d 'MHTOPT': module for Optimal Multiple Hypothesis Testing
d
d  mhtopt implements the optimal multiple-hypothesis-testing (MHT)
d correction  of Viviano, Wuthrich and Niehaus (2026), which
d derives the per-test significance level alpha* from the economic
d incentives of research production rather than treating MHT
d adjustment as ad hoc. Given a cost function for adding hypotheses
d and observations to a study, the package returns the alpha* that
d maximizes the welfare of an evidence-driven decision maker. Two
d cost models are supported: a linear/FDA calibration (default,
d using fixed-cost share parameters from Sertkaya et al. 2016) and
d a Cobb-Douglas calibration (J-PAL parameters from Appendix A of
d the paper). The package provides five commands: mht_critical
d computes alpha* for given J and n; mht_test applies the
d correction to a vector of p-values and compares against
d Bonferroni, Holm, Benjamini-Hochberg, and unadjusted decisions;
d mht_est is a postestimation wrapper that reads e(b) and e(V) from
d any Stata regression; mht_cost_estimate recovers cost parameters
d from project-level data; mht_table reproduces Table 1 of the
d paper. Reference: arXiv:2104.13367. 
d
d KW: hypothesis testing
d KW: multiple hypotheses 
d
d Requires: Stata version 15
d
d Distribution-Date: 20260619
d
d Author: Davide Viviano ,  Harvard University
d Support: email dviviano@@fas.harvard.edu
d
d Author: Kaspar Wuthrich,  Department of Economics, University of Michigan
d Support: email kasparwu@@umich.edu
d
d Author: Paul Niehaus,  UC San Diego
d Support: email pniehaus@@ucsd.edu
d
d Author: Erick Rosas Lopez,   UC San Diego
d Support: email erosaslpez@@ucsd.edu
d
f mht_cost_estimate.ado
